Documentación de la API
Introduction

This document describes how to create, edit, and manage listings using XML listing files and one REST API (.../listing_imports). You can use this API to upload an XML listing file which is imported to create a listing and checked periodically for changes.

The uploaded XML listing file is assigned a Listing Import ID (as opposed to a Listing ID for a published listing on the Airbnb website) and this is the ID you need to use for any further retrieving, updating, or deleting operations via the API.

Please note that you are responsible for maintaining current availability and pricing information in the XML listing file.

To implement Listing Management utilizing XML files, your application must have the vr_feed scope.

Publishing a Listing

Your application can create new listings as well as connect to existing listings that are not API-connected on behalf of a host. You need to obtain OAuth authorization from the host in order to create and manage listings on their behalf. See Getting Started for more information.

When publishing a listing from your application, you have the following options:

  • Create a new listing. You can:
    • Create and automatically publish a new listing.
    • Create a listing and let the host decide whether to publish it as new or merge it with an existing listing.
  • Connect to an existing listing via the API.
Sync Categories

An Airbnb listing that is synced via your application contains a special field called synchronization_category (or sync category), which describes how the listing is being synced.

Category name
 Category value
 Description
Everything
 "sync_all"
 All listing data is synced via your application. hosts cannot modify listing details, pricing or availability on the Airbnb website.
Limited
 "sync_rates_and_availability"
 Only pricing and availability data is synced via your application. Hosts can modify listing details on the Airbnb website, but not pricing and availability data.
Undecided
 "sync_undecided"
 All listing data is synced via your application, but the listing cannot be published. The sync category must be updated to Everything or Limited in order for the listing to be published.
None
 null
 The listing is not API-connected. The host manages the listing directly on the Airbnb website.

Setting of the sync category can be done in two ways:

  • You can set the sync category through the API when publishing a listing from your application. You do so by passing the sync category during the creation of the listing import. You can either allow the listing import job to create a brand new listing with the given sync category or you can provide the id of an existing listing you would like to connect to.
  • Alternatively, you can leave this action to be done by the host on the Airbnb sync page.
Creating a New Listing

The steps below describe the flow for publishing a new listing from your application.

  • Create a listing import: Call the Listing Imports API to create a listing import with an XML listing file. Set the published field to true in the file to trigger publishing of your listing. A listing is created with the requested_approval_status_category set to "new" and the synchronization process between your XML listing file and Airbnb begins. You can also specify the synchronization_category for the listing in the request. You have two options for the synchronization_category:
    • Set it to "sync_all" to mark it as a new listing to be automatically published.
    • Set it to "sync_undecided" (the default value) to let the host decide whether to publish it or merge it with an existing listing.
  • Synchronization and validation: The XML data is parsed and the listing information is validated. If validation is successful, the listing is updated with the information in the XML listing file. If the validation fails, you must address the synchronization error. See Synchronization for more details on how the XML and Airbnb listing data is synchronized and Troubleshooting for more details on handling synchronization errors.
  • Request review: After a successful synchronization, if the published field in the XML listing file is true, Airbnb's automated review is triggered. The review validates the listing against the API Program Listing Requirements. If the listing is rejected, you must address the rejection reason(s) and re-submit for review. Please note that some listings require manual approval, in which case the requested_approval_status_category is set to "ready_for_review". Once these listings are reviewed by Airbnb, you will be notified of the result.
  • Publish: Once the listing is approved, one of three things will occur.
    • If the synchronization_category was set to "sync_all" via the API then it will automatically be published, and has_availability will be set to true.
    • If the synchronization_category is "sync_undecided" and the host has no existing listings on Airbnb that are not API-connected, then the new listing will automatically be published. The sync category will be set to Everything (i.e. "sync_all") and you will receive a Listing Synchronization Settings Updated notification. The host can subsequently change the sync category at any time on the sync page.
    • If the synchronization_category is "sync_undecided" and the host has existing listings on Airbnb that are not API-connected, the host must go to the sync page to ensure a duplicate listing is not created when publishing.
You cannot create a new listing with a Limited sync category. The host must first create the listing on the Airbnb website and then your application can connect to it with a Limited sync category.
Note: If at any time before a listing is published, the published field is set to false, the requested_approval_status_category will be reset to "new".
Merging with an Existing Listing on the Sync Page

If you create a new listing without setting the sync category via the API and the host has existing listings on Airbnb that are not API-connected, the host must go to the Airbnb sync page to choose whether to merge the newly-created listing with an existing listing, or publish it as a new listing.

On the sync page the host can:

  • merge a newly-created API-connected listing with an existing listing on Airbnb, if applicable. Note that the host can only merge with existing listings that they are an owner of, cohosted listings are not supported.
  • choose the sync category for the newly-created API-connected listing and publish it.

You will receive a Listing Synchronization Settings Updated notification whenever the host performs an action on the sync page. See this Help Center article for more information on merging listings using the sync page.

The example below describes what happens when a host merges a newly-created API-connected listing with an existing listing.

  • Your application successfully creates a surrogate listing through the API which gets assigned a listing ID of 12345.
  • On the sync page, the host merges this listing with one of their existing listings with a listing ID of 67890.
  • You receive a Synchronization Settings Changed notification that contains both IDs.
  • Your application is now allowed to edit listing 67890. See Existing Listing Content for details on what happens when the existing listing becomes API-connected.
  • Listing 12345 is deleted.
Connecting to an Existing Listing via the API

You can connect to an existing listing that is not API-connected when publishing from your application through the API. To do so, first retrieve the host's existing listings and provide an interface for the host to map the listing in your software to an existing listing on Airbnb. Then call the Listing Imports API to to create a listing import for that listing.

You can only connect to existing listings owned by the host. You cannot connect to listings that are cohosted by the host.
Retrieving a Host's Existing Listings

You can fetch the host's existing Airbnb listings using the Listings API (the vr_feed scope already includes read access to the listing content APIs, more info here).

  • To retrieve only the listings that are not API-connected, select the listings whose synchronization_category field is null.
  • To retrieve only the listings that the host owns (i.e. is not a cohost of), use the exclude_cohosted query parameter.
Connection Steps

The steps below describe the flow for connecting to an existing listing from your application.

  • Create a listing import for the listing: Call the Listing Imports API to create a listing import with the listing's listing_id and set the synchronization_category to either "sync_all" or "sync_rates_and_availability" (see note below). If the connection is successful, the requested_approval_status_category will be initialized to "new" and the listing will be temporarily unlisted until it is approved. The synchronization process between your XML listing file and the existing listing begins. See Existing Listing Content for details on what happens when the existing listing becomes API-connected.
  • Synchronization and validation: The XML data is parsed and the listing information is validated. If validation is successful, the listing is updated with the information in the XML listing file. If the validation fails, you must address the synchronization error. See Synchronization for more details on how the XML and Airbnb listing data is synchronized and Troubleshooting for more details on handling synchronization errors.
  • Request review: After a successful synchronization, if the published field in the XML listing file is true, Airbnb's automated review is triggered. The review validates the listing against the API Program Listing Requirements. If the listing is rejected, you must address the rejection reason(s) and re-submit for review. Please note that some listings require manual approval, in which case the requested_approval_status_category is set to "ready_for_review". Once these listings are reviewed by Airbnb, you will be notified of the result.
  • Publish: Once the listing is approved, it will automatically be published, i.e. has_availability will be set to true.
Note: If you use "sync_rates_and_availability" and the existing listing's content does not meet the API Program Listing Requirements, the connection will be rejected. The existing listing will be unaffected by the connection attempt.
Note: If at any time before a listing is published, the published field is set to false, the requested_approval_status_category will be reset to "new".
Existing Listing Content

When you connect to an existing listing on Airbnb via the API, or when the host merges a newly-created API-connected listing with an existing listing on the sync page, none of the existing listing's content is replaced. All reservations, reviews, and content of the existing listing remain untouched. Most pricing and availability settings also remain, with the following exceptions:

  • Any imported iCals on the existing listing are unlinked when it becomes API-connected. This may open up dates that were previously blocked by iCals. After the connection is made, check the listing's availability and make necessary updates through API.
  • The existing listing is converted to Instant Book if it was previously Request to Book.
  • Custom pricing and availability settings, such as discounts, seasonal rules and standard fees are cleared as they may not be supported by your application. After the connection is made, perform any updates that are needed.

To update the existing listing's information, make all the necessary listing update calls.

You will not receive any webhook notifications for existing bookings for the newly connected listings. We suggest you perform an initial fetch of all reservations using the Reservations API.

Syncing Only Pricing and Availability

If you only have pricing and availability data for a listing and want to sync that with Airbnb without providing listing content, you can do so using Limited sync.

  • First, the host must create the listing on the Airbnb website if it is not already created. They can enter any valid values for pricing information as these fields will be overwritten when your application connects to the listing. An API-connected host can create listings on the Airbnb website.
  • Once the listing has been created, you can connect to the listing and set the sync category to "sync_rates_and_availability". You do not need to provide any content when you connect to the listing.
  • Your XML listing file when syncing only pricing and availability only needs to contain the pricing, availability and publish nodes. Other nodes are optional for this operation.
  • The listing is now connected with your application and will sync pricing and availability data from it. Any pricing data on the listing prior to the connection is overwritten with data from your application.
Managing a Published Listing
Updating the Sync Category

You can update the sync category of a listing at any time. The host can also update the sync category of a listing after it is published via the sync page. You will receive a Listing Synchronization Settings Updated notification when any changes to the sync category occur.

Updating Limited Sync Listings

For listings with a Limited sync category, only the following fields from the XML listing file are used to update the listing: the published and propertyExternalId fields in the listing node, the guestsIncluded field in the basicDetails node (now available in the pricing node), and all fields in the pricing and availability nodes. However, please note that your XML listing file must contain all fields required for XML validation.

Unlisting Listings

To unlist a listing, set published field to false. This removes the listing from search results and hides it from guests' view. While unlisted, the listing's content will still be updated. To re-list the listing, set the published field back to true.

Disconnecting (Unlinking) Listings

An API-connected listing can be disconnected from your application at any time. The host can do this on the sync page using the “Stop Sync” button. Your application can do so by deleting the listing import but keeping the listing on Airbnb (see Deleting a Listing Import). Once disconnected, the host must manage the listing directly on the Airbnb website. You will receive a Listings Unlinked notification when a listing is disconnected from your application.

The host cannot reverse a stop sync. If the host wants to resume managing the listing through your application, you must connect to the listing again.
Deleting Listings

You can choose to completely delete a listing. See Deleting a Listing Import. This removes both the Listing Import object and the associated listing. You will receive a Listings Unlinked notification when the listing is disconnected from your application.

Disconnecting the Host's Account from your Application

Your application can be disconnected from the host's account at any time. You can do this by revoking their token and the host can perform this action from their Account Settings. When this occurs, all the host's listings will be disconnected from your application and you will lose access to the host's account. You will receive an Authorization Revoked notification when a host's account is disconnected from your application.

Listing Synchronization

Synchronization happens when Airbnb downloads and attempts to validate your imported XML listing file and check it for content requirements. The first time this happens is when a new Airbnb listing is created.

Synchronization Initiation

An XML listing file synchronization is initiated in one of 4 ways:

  • When a Listing Import is first created through the API.
  • When a synchronization's scheduled time arrives (hourly, daily, etc.). You can set how often this occurs with the synchronization_frequency parameter.
  • When an immediate synchronization is requested using Listing Import API’s on_demand_synchronization_requested flag.
  • When a potential guest enters the payment information page during a booking process. For this kind of synchronization, Airbnb updates the pricing and availability.
Synchronization Process
  • A synchronization is initiated (see above).
  • Airbnb attempts to retrieve your XML listing file via HTTPS.
  • If the file has not changed, nothing further happens. Otherwise, any updates are pushed to its associated Airbnb listing.
    Note: A change is defined as an XML listing file update or Airbnb's ability to once again access the same document (if hadn't been able to before due to a server being down or other problem). Once access is restored, Airbnb again checks the file and pushes any updates.
  • A new listing is created if this is the file's first synchronization. Once created, you can see the listing's ID when you retrieve your XML listing file via the .../listing_imports API.
  • If the update succeeds, nothing further happens.
  • If the update fails, it is immediately retried three more times. After four failed attempts, the listing is taken offline and nothing happens until the next validation/sync is initiated. Once re-validated, the listing is again synced and put back online.
Pre-booking synchronization job

When a guest attempts to book a property, Airbnb makes a best effort to make sure the listing is up-to-date with your XML listing file.

  • A quick check is performed while the guest is providing payment information, so that, when the user finalizes the booking, the calendar and pricing is up-to-date.
  • If the date the guest is trying to book is blocked in the updated document, the guest is not be able to book the requested dates.
  • There is a small window between when the guest starts providing payment information and finalizing booking where the listing may be out-of-date because the XML listing file is updated after synchronization but before booking. Though unlikely, the possibility remains.
  • Other information, such as pictures and descriptions, are not synchronized. Those updates are not picked up until the next full synchronization.
API Program Listing Requirements

In addition to the XML schema and listing validations, all listings published via the API are subject to our Listing API Program Policies. Any listing that fails to meet the requirements of the policies will not be approved for publishing.

For listings that require registration, the Listings Registration API is available for XML partners.

Notes on Testing
Creating Test Listings

Do not create test listings under the Airbnb partner account (i.e. the account that owns the test application). Instead, create a new Airbnb account and authorize your test application for access.

Always authorize your test application with your test user account before creating test listings with that account. Once you authorize your test application with the account, any listings created with that account will only be visible to your test users. Furthermore, these listings will not be subject to our fake inventory monitors. Creating test listings without first authorizing your test application with the test user account could result in those listings being deleted by our fake inventory monitors.

Testing Checklist

Before granting supply partners access to a production application, Airbnb will verify that they have completed the following listing management checklist using their test application.

Onboarding listings
  • Create listings that both meet and don’t meet our minimum standards.
  • Confirm receipt of listing approval notifications (both approval and rejections).
  • Publish at least 5 listings. Make sure to test all variations:
    • publishing a new listing with full sync and with with limited sync
    • connecting to an existing listing with full and with limited sync. When connecting to existing listings make sure to import all current reservations. Tip: a quick way to create listings to use for connecting to is to stop sync some API listings, which will disconnect them from your application.
  • Confirm the receipt of the Synchronization Settings notifications.
Managing Listings
  • Make sure you can successfully unlist and relist listings.
  • Try unlinking (stop sync) several listings. Confirm the receipt of unlinked notifications.
  • Try unlinking the entire account in two ways: by revoking a token, and by clicking Disconnect under Connected Apps as a host. Confirm the receipt of the authorization revoked notification.
Rate Limits

Please first review the general API Rate Limiting requirements and ways to handle such issues.

  • We have rate limiting requirements for each partner.
  • The limit is 1000 calendar availability and price updates per min for each partner.
  • If partner reaches the limit, partner will receive the 429 rate limit error.
Listing Import API

This section details the API calls you can make to create and manage listings using XML listing files.

Before you begin making .../listing_imports API calls, you need to create XML listing files that describe the listing information. Please refer to the XML Listing Schema and the sections describing each node that follow. You can also see a full XML File Example.

Creating a Listing Import

You can use this endpoint to let Airbnb know your XML listing file's location, which needs to be publicly-accessible via HTTPS. This call triggers an initial synchronization but the job is asynchronous, so you will only be able to see the result after some time (usually several seconds).

POST /v2/listing_imports

 Description

required

document_uri
string
required
 Document's fully qualified URI which must be publicly accessible and must be accessible via HTTPS. Must be unique for each listing import.
synchronization_frequency
string
required
 How frequently this document for be crawled for changes. Only supported strings are accepted.
synchronization_category
string
optional, default is sync_undecided
 If you are creating a new listing, use one of "sync_all" or "sync_undecided". If you are connecting to an existing listing use one of "sync_all" or "sync_rates_and_availability".
listing_id
string
optional
 The id of an existing, not API connected, listing that you would like to connect to. The listing must be owned by the host. You must pass the synchronization_category. If you are trying to connect with limited sync, the existing listing content will be validated against our API program listing requirements before allowing the connection.

Deletes an existing listing import. You can choose between deleting the associated listing or keeping the associated listing as manual.

NOTE: Deleting the listing will fail if it has at least one upcoming reservation.

Listing Import Document API

A listing import document represents a snapshot of a listing import crawl. Each successful crawl that finds a change in the source XML listing file is given a new version and cached for debugging purposes. We store the documents for the last 30 days.
This API allows developers to query the historical versions and verify changes as seen by Airbnb, e.g. check what prices Airbnb saw in the XML at the time of a reservation.

curl -X "GET" "https://api.airbnb.com/v2/listing_import_documents?listing_import_id=1" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "X-Airbnb-Oauth-Token: 8uaxi4r1busbeg21fuacga40c" \
  -H "X-Airbnb-API-Key: av8mf8kd4k40fq26xxd9w4p44"
Example Response
{
  "listing_import_documents": [
    {
      "document_uri": "https://example.com/listing-1.xml",
      "download_uri": "https://airbnb-services-production.s3.amazonaws.com/…",
      "first_synchronization_at": "2016-02-18T21:50:58+00:00",
      "id": "1/1",
      "last_synchronization_at": "2016-02-18T21:50:58+00:00",
      "listing_import_id": 1,
      "version": 1
    }
  ]
}
Listing Import Document Object
Field
 Description
id
integer
 The id of this document version. Composed of listing_import_id and version
version
integer
 A monotonically increasing value representing an exact snapshot of the associated listing import.
listing_import_id
integer
 The id of the listing import associated with this document.
download_uri
string
 URI to download a copy of the document that was crawled and cached by Airbnb.
document_uri
string
 The fully qualified URI that Airbnb accessed to create this document version.
first_synchronization_at
string
 ISO-8601 formatted string representing the first time Airbnb encountered this version of the document.
last_synchronization_at
string
 ISO-8601 formatted string representing the last time Airbnb crawled this version document.

            <xs:enumeration value="MIN_NIGHTS" />
            <xs:enumeration value="MAX_NIGHTS" />
            <xs:enumeration value="CLOSED_FOR_CHECKIN" />
            <xs:enumeration value="CLOSED_FOR_CHECKOUT" />
          </xs:restriction>
        </xs:simpleType>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="value" type="xs:positiveInteger" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1" />
      <xs:element name="daysOfWeek" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1">
        <xs:simpleType>
          <xs:restriction base="xs:string">
            <xs:pattern value="((MONDAY|TUESDAY|WEDNESDAY|THURSDAY|FRIDAY|SATURDAY|SUNDAY)(,(MONDAY|TUESDAY|WEDNESDAY|THURSDAY|FRIDAY|SATURDAY|SUNDAY))*)|UNSPECIFIED" />
          </xs:restriction>
        </xs:simpleType>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="startDate" type="xs:date" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1" />

    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

    <xs:sequence>
      <!-- support up to 18 months(550 days); max guest number is 16 -->

    <xs:restriction base="xs:string">
      <!-- matches: 2019-02-28,1,100,200,300,... -->
      <!-- guest number should >=1 and <=16; length of stay should >=1 and <=28 -->
      <xs:pattern value="([12]\d{3}-(0[1-9]|1[0-2])-(0[1-9]|[12]\d|3[01])),([1-9]|1[0-6]),(\d+,){0,27}\d+" />

  </xs:simpleType>

pricingRule

With Pricing Rules, you can set the following types of pricing adjustment or discount rules to be applied to your highest precedence daily rate (i.e rules are applied on top of custom pricing). Note that an “adjustment” can be either positive or negative.

  • Seasonal adjustment - A percentage or fixed dollar amount applied to the base nightly price (daily or custom price). For example, if they book during Christmas week when demand is high, they have to pay 40 USD more per night. This new nightly price is referred to as the adjusted seasonal price.
  • Length-of-stay adjustment - A percentage or fixed dollar amount applied to the adjusted seasonal price if they stay a specified length of time. Overwrites weekly/monthly discounts. For example, if they stay more than 20 nights, they pay 10% more. If the adjusted seasonal price is $100, then the new nightly price is $100.
  • Last-minute discount - Modify the adjusted seasonal price by a percentage or fixed dollar amount if guests book within a specified date/time of their stay. For example, if they book a week or less before their stay, they get a 10% nightly discount. If the adjusted seasonal price is $100, then the new nightly price is $90.
  • Booking-ahead discount - Deduct a percentage or fixed dollar amount from the adjusted seasonal price if they book before a specified date/time before their stay. For example, if they book 60 days before their stay, they get a $20 nightly discount. If the adjusted seasonal price is $100, then the new nightly price is $80.
If you use both monthly/weekly price factors and LOS pricing rules, note that we treat monthly and weekly price factors as default LOS rules. Thus, either use only one of these or be careful to avoid unexpected conflicts.
For examples and more details on how pricing rules are applied see the appendix section about Applying Pricing Rules.

seasonalPricingGroup

You can use a Seasonal Pricing Group to apply pricing rules to a specific date period. During those periods, seasonal pricing rules override default pricing rules of the SAME TYPE for the date ranges applied.

For example, let's say you have default weekly and monthly Length-of-Stay discounts and a default 10% Seasonal Adjustment. If you then choose to set a weekly Length-of-Stay discount in seasonalPricingGroup for October, then the default weekly and monthly length-of-stay discounts no longer apply, though the default Seasonal Adjustment does.

To clear all the rule groups, update seasonalPricingGroups as an empty node <seasonalPricingGroups />

passThroughFees

Partners can provide Standard fees that will apply to reservations on top of the stay price. Fees can be specified as either percentage of the nightly price (after all adjustments) or a flat amount per reservation.

Fee Name
 Guest Display (where each fee is mapped)
Resort fee
 Nightly price
Community Fee
 Nightly price
Management fee
 Nightly price
Linen fee
 Cleaning fee

In order to streamline the guest experience, the fees will not be shown as separate line items. Our system performs the calculation for the fee and they are included in the nightly rate or cleaning fee when shown to guests. However, Airbnb provide a detailed breakdown of these fees in reservation webhook notifications (see Reservation Object), so Airbnb transactions will be more consistent with a property manager's existing accounting structure. Airbnb currently supports 4 types of fees.

Fees are subject to the same taxes/fees and cancellation/refund policies as the price type they're mapped to. All applicable taxes and the Airbnb host and guest fees will be applied. Fees will inherit the cancellation/refund policy of the price type they're mapped to. For example, cleaning fees are refunded if a guest cancels before the reservation starts; this will apply to the linen fee as well. Similarly, if a strict cancellation policy refunds 50% of the stay price, we will refund 50% of any resort fees charged.

If you have previously been manually customizing the base price to include any of the above fee types, remember to reduce the base price by the relevant amount after developing to standard fees. This ensures that you are not “double-charging” the fee.

availabilityRule

We support the following types of availability rules:

  • Days of the week (Mon-Sun) when guests cannot check-in
  • Days of the week (Mon-Sun) when guests cannot check-out
  • For each day of the week (Mon-Sun), the maximum nights guests can stay if they check-in on that day. Note that this rule is only available for seasonal rule groups, not default availability rules.
  • For each day of the week (Mon-Sun), the minimum nights guest have to stay if they check-in on that day
Custom daily changeover values marking the dates as unavailable for checkin/checkout overwrite default/seasonal availability rules for checkin and checkout, if the latter mark days as available. Custom daily changeover values marking the dates as available for checkin/checkout don't overwrite seasonal/default availability rules if the latter mark days as unavailable.
For more details on how availability rules are applied see the appendix section about Applying Availability Rules.
Elements
Field
 Description
type
string
required
 One of:
"MIN_NIGHTS", "MAX_NIGHTS", "CLOSED_FOR_CHECKIN", "CLOSED_FOR_CHECKOUT"
value
integer
optional
 Specifies the number of nights for min and max nights rules. Omit for other rules.
daysOfWeek
string
required
 Comma-separated days of the week that this rule applies to. Use "MONDAY", "TUESDAY", "WEDNESDAY", "THURSDAY", "FRIDAY", "SATURDAY", or "SUNDAY". For the min/max nights rule types, you can use "UNSPECIFIED" to represent the days that you haven't specified this rule for. In order to specify min/max nights rules, your nodes must cumulatively cover all days of the week or have one node that includes "UNSPECIFIED". Please note that "UNSPECIFIED" is not supported for "CLOSED_FOR_CHECKOUT" and "CLOSED_FOR_CHECKIN".
Example
<availabilityRule>
   <type>MIN_NIGHTS</type>
   <value>3</value>
   <daysOfWeek>SUNDAY,MONDAY,FRIDAY</daysOfWeek>
</availabilityRule>
<availabilityRule>
   <type>MIN_NIGHTS</type>
   <value>7</value>
   <daysOfWeek>UNSPECIFIED</daysOfWeek>
</availabilityRule>

 Comma separated change over settings for each day of the period. D is default (can check in and checkout), I is can check in only, O is can check out only, and N is no check in or checkout.

 Start date in the YYYY-MM-DD format

 End date in the YYYY-MM-DD format (the date is inclusive)

Detailed requirements for dailyAvailableCount:

  • It is strongly recommended that you pass in a totalInventoryCount on the availability node when passing in dailyAvailableCount. The values in dailyAvailableCount must not exceed the totalInventoryCount.
  • Although both dailyAvailabilityCount and dailyAvailability are optional, you must pass in at least one of them in order for your listing to be imported. We suggest you always pass in both fields to get best control of your listing. The table below shows the requirements for valid dailyAvailability and dailyAvailableCount values:
Possible values for dailyAvailability
 Allowed values for dailyAvailableCount
 Notes
"A"
>0, <=500
 - On listing's calendar, this date will be marked as "available"; all availability rules will be overwritten.
"U"
>=0
 - On listing's calendar, this date will be marked as "unavailable"; all availability rules will be overwritten.
- A positive dailyAvailableCount can be used for stop sale.
"D"
>=0
 - If dailyAvailableCount = 0, this date will be blocked on calendar as "unavailable".
- If dailyAvailableCount > 0, the availability of this date will conform to the availability rules.
Example
<availabilityPeriod>
   <dateRange>
      <startDate>2015-12-20</startDate>
      <endDate>2015-12-31</endDate>
   </dateRange>
   <periodMinNights>3</periodMinNights>
   <dailyAvailability>D,A,U,D,A,A,A,A,A,A,A,D</dailyAvailability>
   <dailyChangeOver>D,D,I,I,I,I,N,N,O,O,O,D</dailyChangeOver>
</availabilityPeriod>
XML LOS Records

As an alternative to seasonal pricing and availability rule groups, you can set a listing's pricing and availability for specified date/time periods by using a list of length-of-stay records (LOS records). Using LOS records allows for more flexibility in setting pricing and availability for specific dates and stays than seasonal rule groups.

For more details on how applying LOS records interacts with other pricing and availability rules, see the appendix section about Applying LOS Records.
losRecords
Elements
Field
 Description
r
string
required
 A comma separated string representing the LOS prices for a certain check in date and a certain max guest number. See the LOS Record Data Format section for more details. There must be at least 1 and up to 8800 r elements in a losRecords node.
Example
<losRecords>
    <r>2019-01-01,1,100,210,0,390,550,580,0,820</r>
    <r>2019-01-01,2,200,410,0,690,1050,1080,0,1620</r>
    <r>2019-01-01,4,400,810,0,1290,1550,1580,0,1820</r>
    <r>2019-01-01,6,600,1620,2350,3500,0,4230,4750,5240</r>
    <r>2019-01-02,1,100,210,0,390,550,580,0,820</r>
</losRecords>
When applying LOS records, you must also provide a base nightly rate for the listing using the Pricing API. This value will only be used to display the price when guests search without dates and does not impact availability.
LOS Record Data Format

The general format for each string in the los_records array is:

<checkin date>,<max guest number>,<1 night price>,<2 nights price>,<3 nights price>,...
Example
2019-01-01,1,100,210,0,390,550,580,0,820

If 1 guest checks in on 2019-01-01, the price for staying 1 night would be 100, the price for 2 nights would be 210, and staying 3 nights is not available.

2019-01-01,2,200,410,0,690,1050,1080,0,1620

Same as above, but this record indicates the prices for 2 guests checking in on 2019-01-01.

2019-01-01,4,400,810,0,1290,1550,1580,0,1820

Same as above, but this record indicates the prices for >2 and <=4 guests.

2019-01-01,5,0

The listing is not available for 5 guests if check-in date is 2019-01-01.

2019-01-01,6,600,1620,2350,3500,0,4230,4750,5240

Prices for 6 guests if check-in date is 2019-01-01.

2019-01-02,1,100,210,0,390,550,580,0,820

Prices for 1 guest if check-in date is 2019-01-02.

2019-01-02,4,300,610,0,990,1550,1580,0,2020

Prices for >1 and <=4 guests if check-in date is 2019-01-02.

Note that:

  • The check-in date should be within the next 18 months (550 days). If the LOS records do not contain prices for certain check-in dates, we will mark these dates as not available for check-in.
  • The guest number is the max guest number (please see the example on third row). This number should be an integer >=1 and <=16, as bookings on Airbnb usually do not differentiate the prices beyond 16 guests.
  • For any combination of check-in date and max guest number, we support up to 28 days' length-of-stay prices. This is a maximum cap; you can send prices for >=1 and <=28 nights. If the LOS records do not contain prices for certain length-of-stays, we will mark these dates as not available for check-in. For stays longer than 28 days, we will mark days as unavailable.
  • If the LOS records do not contain data for certain dates, either as check-in dates or as part of a stay, we will mark these dates as unavailable.
  • Each price should be an integer. If the listing is not available for a particular length-of-stay, the price should be set to 0.

Appendix
Room Type Inventory

Some properties might have multiple rooms for a certain room type. For these listings, partners can provide Airbnb with a listing's total inventory count, daily available count for specific dates, as well as property external id. Note that the property type house is not eligible for Room Type Inventory.

Representative Inventory Attributes:

field
 description
 required
totalInventoryCount
Total number of rooms for a room type. The maximum count is 500.
 No, but strongly recommended if data is available
dailyAvailableCount
Total number of rooms per day. The maximum count is 500.
 Yes
propertyExternalId
ID of the hotel property. This allows Airbnb to group different room types of a same property together.
 Yes
Example Schema - set property external id
<listing>
  ...
  <propertyExternalId>Hotel1234</propertyExternalId>
</listing>
Example Schema - set total inventory count
<availability>
  ...
  <totalInventoryCount>11</totalInventoryCount>
</availability>
Example schema - set daily available count
<availabilityPeriods>
  <availabilityPeriod>
    <dateRange>
       <startDate>2015-12-20</startDate>
       <endDate>2015-12-31</endDate>
    </dateRange>
    <dailyAvailablity>D,A,D,U,U....</dailyAvailability>
    <dailyAvailableCount>4,5,9,0,2....</dailyAvailabilityCount>
    <dailyChangeOver required>...</dailyChangeOver>
  </availabilityPeriod>
  ...
  <availabilityPeriod>
    <dateRange>
       <startDate>2016-01-02</startDate>
       <endDate>2016-01-03</endDate>
    </dateRange>
    <dailyAvailability>D,A,D,U,U....</dailyAvailability>
    <dailyAvailableCount>4,7,10,0,2....</dailyAvailabilityCount>
    <dailyChangeOver required>...</dailyChangeOver>
  </availabilityPeriod>
</availabilityPeriods>
Applying Pricing Rules
Setting an Adjusted Seasonal Price

You can apply a percentage or fixed dollar amount change to the nightly price of highest precedence (base or custom) to get the nightly adjusted seasonal price. This can add to, or subtract from, the base nightly price.

Example: This rule adjusts the base nightly price 20% higher. If the default nightly price is $100 USD, then the adjusted seasonal price is $120 USD.

<pricingRule>
  <type>SEASONAL_ADJUSTMENT</type>
  <priceChange>
    <amount>20</amount>
    <type>PERCENT</type>
  </priceChange>
</pricingRule>
Setting a Length-of-Stay Adjustment

If a stay is X days or more, you can increase or decrease the adjusted seasonal price a percentage or fixed dollar amount. This is similar to existing long-term adjustments applied to trips that are at least 7 days and 28 days respectively. This rule is applied to the longest day matched. This discount is shown to guests.

Example: This rule says this if the guest stays at least 3 nights, then they get a 20% nightly discount. If the adjusted seasonal price is $100 USD, then the new discounted price is $80 USD.

<pricingRule>
  <type>STAYED_AT_LEAST_X_DAYS</type>
  <threshold>3</threshold>
  <priceChange>
    <amount>-20</amount>
    <type>PERCENT</type>
  </priceChange>
</pricingRule>
Setting a Last-Minute Discount

You can offer percentage or fixed dollar amount discounts to trips that are booked X days or less before a stay. This discount is not shown to guests.

Example: If the guest books 3 days or less before their stay, this rule entitles them to a $20 nightly discount. If the adjusted seasonal price is $100 USD, then the new discounted price is $80 USD.

<pricingRule>
  <type>BOOKED_WITHIN_AT_MOST_X_DAYS</type>
  <threshold>3</threshold>
  <priceChange>
    <amount>-20</amount>
    <type>ABSOLUTE</type>
  </priceChange>
</pricingRule>
Setting a Booking-Ahead Discount

You can offer percentage or fixed dollar amount discounts to trips that are booked X days or more in advance. This discount is not shown to guests.

Example: If the guest books 60 nights or more in advance, this rule entitles them to $20 per night discount. If the adjusted seasonal price is $120 USD, then the new discounted price is $100 USD.

<pricingRule>
  <type>BOOKED_BEYOND_AT_LEAST_X_DAYS</type>
  <threshold>60</threshold>
  <priceChange>
    <amount>-20</amount>
    <type>ABSOLUTE</type>
  </priceChange>
</pricingRule>
Calculating the Final Price

Adjusted seasonal price = Seasonal price adjustment applied to base nightly price.

Final price = Additional price adjustments applied to the adjusted seasonal price.

Suppose for a certain date range, the following pricing rules are created:

Base nightly price = $200

  • Seasonal adjusted discount = -10%, nightly discount = -(200 * .10) = -20

Adjusted seasonal price = 200 - 20 = $180

  • Long-term adjustment = -20, nightly discount = -20
  • Last-minute discount = -2%, nightly discount = -(180 * .02 ) = -3.6
  • Booking-ahead discount = -2%, nightly discount = -(180 * .02) = -3.6

Final price = 180 - 20 - 3.6 - 3.6 = $152.8

Staying Across Seasons

Pricing rules are resolved on a per day basis. For a listing with base price $100, suppose there is 5% discount from 5/1 - 5/5, and $10 discount from 5/8 - 5/10. If the stay is from 5/1 - 5/10, it will get 5% off from 5/1 - 5/5, no discounts from 5/6 - 5/7, and $10 off for each day from 5/8 - 5/10. Thus, the total cost of the stay is 100 * (1-0.05) * 5 + 100 * 2 + (100 - 10) * 3 = 945.

Applying Availability Rules
Setting When Guests Cannot Check-in

You can set which days of the week guests cannot check-in.

Example: The following XML indicates that guests cannot check-in on Monday and Friday:

<availabilityRules>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>CLOSED_FOR_CHECKIN</type>
        <daysOfWeek>MONDAY,FRIDAY</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
</availabilityRules>
Setting When Guests Cannot Check-out

You can set which days of the week guests cannot check-out.

Example: The following XML indicates that guests cannot check-out on Sunday:

<availabilityRules>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>CLOSED_FOR_CHECKOUT</type>
        <daysOfWeek>SUNDAY</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
</availabilityRules>
Setting the Minimum Nights Guests Have to Stay

You can set the minimum number of nights guests have to stay depending on which day of the week they check-in.

Example: The following XML sets two rules:

  • If the guest checks-in on Sunday, Tuesday, Friday or Saturday, they have to stay for 5 nights minimum.
  • For all other days, the guest has to stay for 3 nights minimum. UNSPECIFIED indicates that this applies to all days that haven't had a value specifically set.
<availabilityRules>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>MIN_NIGHTS</type>
        <value>5</value>
        <daysOfWeek>SUNDAY,TUESDAY,FRIDAY,SATURDAY</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>MIN_NIGHTS</type>
        <value>3</value>
        <daysOfWeek>UNSPECIFIED</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
</availabilityRules>
Setting the Maximum Nights Guests can Stay

You can set the maximum number of nights guests can stay depending on which day of the week they check-in.

Example: The following XML sets two rules:

  • If the guest checks-in on Monday, Wednesday or Thursday, they can stay for 8 nights maximum.
  • For all other days, the guest can stay for 6 nights minimum. UNSPECIFIED indicates that this applies to all days that haven't had a value specifically set.
<availabilityRules>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>MAX_NIGHTS</type>
        <value>8<value>
        <daysOfWeek>MONDAY, WEDNESDAY,THURSDAY</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
    <availabilityRule>
        <type>MAX_NIGHTS</type>
        <value>6<value>
        <daysOfWeek>UNSPECIFIED</daysOfWeek>
    </availabilityRule>
</availabilityRules>

NOTES

When you specify MIN_NIGHTS or MAX_NIGHTS, you must either:

  • Provide rules for all 7 days of week, or
  • Provide at least one rule with UNSPECIFIED that sets a default for unspecified days
Applying LOS Records
Interaction with Pricing and Availability APIs

If you use LOS records to set a listing's price and availability, some of the parameters in the Pricing Settings API, Availability Rules API and Calendar Settings API must be omitted. The following sections indicate which parameters will no longer be supported, since you will consolidate pricing and availability features into LOS records instead of using other API calls.

Please make sure to omit the unused parameters in the API calls when updating listings that are using LOS records, otherwise errors might be raised. If you are managing listings that are not using LOS records, then those listings may continue using all existing pricing and availability rules.

Interaction with the Availability Rules API

We will continue supporting all existing availability rules for listings using LOS records.

For any combination of [check-in date, guest number, length of stay], if the LOS record price is 0 then we will mark it as unavailable, and all the other Availability Rules will not be able to change it. However, if the LOS record shows this date as available, the other Availability Rules will be applied on top. This may add additional restrictions to the date and possibly render it unavailable for certain stays.

If a date is not included in any LOS record, either as a date available for check-in or as a date available for a stay, we will mark it as unavailable.

Interaction with the Calendars API and Calendar Batch Operations API

If using these endpoints to set availability on a daily basis, please make sure the daily availability is consistent with the LOS records.

Interaction with Nightly Prices, Standard Fees and Discounts
  • Stay price adjustments for seasonal pricing, length of stay discounts, or any other price adjustment that are not supported by Seasonal Rule Groups can be incorporated into LOS records.
  • Standard fees should be sent separately so they can be itemized during the guest checkout flow.
  • Discounts that need to be displayed separately to guests should be sent separately and will be applied on top of the LOS record prices.
Troubleshooting and Best Practices
Troubleshooting

We send a daily email that notifies you if any listings have been taken down because of XML errors. If you receive this email, please take action to resolve the error. Until you do, guests cannot book your listing.

First, you should look at the error information using the .../listing_imports API.

To retrieve error information:

  • Make an API call to retrieve your XML listing file. See Retrieving a Listing Import
  • In the response returned, check the last_synchronization_error field.
Best Practices

For best results, follow these practices:

  • Test your end-to-end process - Until you are familiar with creating listings, set published to false. Once you are confident in your process and are ready for listings to be published, set this field to true.
  • Synchronization frequency - Use the synchronization frequency that your server can tolerate. hourly is recommended since your calendar and pricing is updated when a guest makes a booking request. There is no need to worry about the calendar being out-of-sync.
  • Immediate update - To update the listing immediately after making changes to the XML listing file, you can set the on_demand_synchronization_requested flag to true. This feature should be used for debugging purposes only. Note that the sync this call initiates is run asynchronously and you won't see the results in the response. To get the results, you should then make a Retrieving a Listing Import call. With this call, you are limited to 120 on-demand requests per hour.
FAQ
  • Am I allowed to reuse XML listing file URIs?
    No, but you can always change the document_uri field, then update your XML listing file.
  • If a XML listing file works correctly, then something changes and your crawl no longer correctly validates it, what happens to the listing?
    We will retry up to three times to process the file. After three attempts, if the document still fails, the listing is taken offline. For more information, see Listing Synchronization Overview.
  • Why are some dates blocked when the XML says they are available?
    If a host cancels or initiates alterations to a reservation’s start/end dates, the original dates stay blocked. A host can contact Airbnb to have the dates re-opened on the calendar. See here for more information about penalties
